---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Glorious Hearts Case Study | Ross Lyall Portfolio"
  description="Case study for Glorious Hearts, an Astro football archive website."
>
  <div class="page-shell">
    <main>
      <section class="case-hero case-hero--hearts">
        <a class="back-link" href="/">← Back to portfolio</a>

        <p class="eyebrow">Case Study / Website / Football Archive</p>
        <h1>Glorious Hearts</h1>
        <p class="case-hero__lead">
          A structured Hearts season archive built with Astro, bringing together
          fixtures, match pages, player profiles, galleries and supporter
          storytelling.
        </p>

        <div class="case-meta">
          <span>Astro</span>
          <span>Static Data</span>
          <span>Vercel</span>
          <span>Responsive Design</span>
          <span>Football Archive</span>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-showcase">
        <div class="mock-browser">
          <div class="mock-browser__bar">
            <span></span>
            <span></span>
            <span></span>
          </div>

          <div class="mock-screen" style="background: var(--hearts);">
            <span class="mock-screen__label">Season archive</span>
            <h2 class="mock-screen__heading">
              Matches, players, galleries and memories.
            </h2>

            <div class="mock-ui-grid">
              <div class="mock-ui-card mock-ui-card--wide"></div>
              <div class="mock-ui-card"></div>
              <div class="mock-ui-card"></div>
              <div class="mock-ui-card"></div>
              <div class="mock-ui-card"></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="mock-phone">
          <div class="mock-phone__screen">
            <div class="mock-phone__pill"></div>
            <div class="mock-phone__button">Match archive</div>
            <div class="mock-phone__button">Player profiles</div>
            <div class="mock-phone__button">Gallery</div>
            <div class="mock-phone__button">My story</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-overview">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">The problem</p>
          <h2>
            A football season has loads of detail, but it is easy for it to
            become scattered.
          </h2>
        </div>

        <div class="case-copy">
          <p>
            Glorious Hearts was built as a personal archive for a Hearts season,
            bringing matches, scorers, player information, images and supporter
            memories into one structured website.
          </p>

          <p>
            Instead of treating the season as a simple list of fixtures, the aim
            was to make it feel like a living archive: part record, part
            gallery, part story of following the club.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-overview">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">The solution</p>
          <h2>A fast static site powered by structured football data.</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="case-copy">
          <p>
            The site uses Astro to generate a fast, content-led archive. Match
            and player information is held as structured data, making it easier
            to build repeatable pages without manually designing every match
            from scratch.
          </p>

          <p>
            This makes the project easier to maintain over a season: new matches
            can be added to the data, and the site can display them consistently
            across the homepage, archive lists, match pages and player sections.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">Key features</p>
          <h2>What Glorious Hearts includes</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="feature-grid">
          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>01</span>
            <h3>Match archive</h3>
            <p>
              Fixtures and results are organised into a season archive, making
              it easy to browse matches by date and competition.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>02</span>
            <h3>Match pages</h3>
            <p>
              Individual match pages can show key details such as scoreline,
              scorers, penalties, images and match-specific notes.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>03</span>
            <h3>Player profiles</h3>
            <p>
              Player pages help turn the site from a fixture list into a fuller
              season archive with squad information and season context.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>04</span>
            <h3>Image galleries</h3>
            <p>
              Match images and gallery sections give the archive a stronger
              visual identity and make it feel more personal.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>05</span>
            <h3>Supporter story</h3>
            <p>
              Personal writing and memory sections add context beyond the data,
              connecting the project to the experience of following Hearts.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>06</span>
            <h3>Responsive layout</h3>
            <p>
              The site is designed to work cleanly on desktop and mobile, with
              match and player content still easy to read on smaller screens.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-overview">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">Design thinking</p>
          <h2>
            The site needed to feel like a football archive, not just a blog.
          </h2>
        </div>

        <div class="case-copy">
          <p>
            The design focuses on structure and repeatability. A football season
            naturally creates repeated content — matches, players, galleries and
            stats — so the site was built around reusable layouts and central
            data.
          </p>

          <p>
            The goal was to make the archive easy to update while still feeling
            emotional and personal. Data gives the site structure; memories and
            images give it character.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">Build approach</p>
          <h2>How the site is organised</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="flow-grid flow-grid--four">
          <article class="flow-card">
            <span>01</span>
            <h3>Central data</h3>
            <p>
              Match and player information is stored in structured data files so
              it can be reused across multiple parts of the site.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="flow-card">
            <span>02</span>
            <h3>Reusable layouts</h3>
            <p>
              Components and page templates keep the design consistent across
              match pages, player pages and archive sections.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="flow-card">
            <span>03</span>
            <h3>Static output</h3>
            <p>
              Astro generates a fast static website, making it simple to deploy,
              browse and maintain.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="flow-card">
            <span>04</span>
            <h3>Season updates</h3>
            <p>
              The archive can grow throughout the season by adding new match
              data, images and page content.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">What I learned</p>
          <h2>Useful lessons from building it</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="lesson-list">
          <article>
            <h3>Structured data makes content sites much easier to maintain</h3>
            <p>
              Once match and player details were centralised, it became easier
              to display the same information consistently across the whole
              site.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article>
            <h3>
              Personal projects still need proper information architecture
            </h3>
            <p>
              Even though the subject was personal, the site worked best when it
              was treated like a real archive with clear sections and repeatable
              patterns.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article>
            <h3>Static sites are ideal for archives</h3>
            <p>
              Astro was a strong fit because the site needed to be fast,
              reliable and content-focused without requiring a complex backend.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-next">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">Future improvements</p>
          <h2>Where Glorious Hearts could go next</h2>
        </div>

        <ul>
          <li>Add richer season statistics and player appearance summaries.</li>
          <li>Expand match galleries and supporter memory sections.</li>
          <li>Add more filtering for competitions, scorers and match types.</li>
          <li>Improve long-term archive navigation across multiple seasons.</li>
          <li>Add more automated references or source links for match data.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>
    </main>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
